  "prompt": "Which is the best book for learning Python 3 for absolute beginners?",
  "response": "For absolute beginners looking to learn Python 3, one of the most highly recommended books is **\"Python Crash Course\" by Eric Matthes**. Here\u2019s why it stands out:\n\n1. **Comprehensive yet Concise**: The book covers a wide range of topics from basic to more advanced concepts, making it suitable for beginners while also providing enough depth for those who want to go further.\n\n2. **Practical Examples**: It includes numerous examples and exercises that help reinforce the concepts taught in each chapter.\n\n3. **Up-to-date**: The book is regularly updated to reflect the latest versions of Python 3, ensuring you learn the most current practices.\n\n4. **Structured Learning**: The content is organized in a way that builds upon previous chapters, making it easier to follow and understand.\n\n5. **Real-world Applications**: It covers practical applications like data analysis and visualization, which can be very motivating for beginners to see how Python is used in real-world scenarios.\n\nAnother excellent option for beginners is **\"Automate the Boring Stuff with Python\" by Al Sweigart**. This book is particularly appealing if you're interested in practical applications right from the start.\n\n- **Focus on Practicality**: It teaches Python through real-world tasks like automating file management, working with spreadsheets, and web scraping.\n- **Engaging**: The book is written in an engaging style that makes learning fun and less intimidating for beginners.\n\nBoth of these books are highly praised and widely recommended for those starting with Python 3. The best choice depends on your learning style and what motivates you to learn. If you prefer a comprehensive guide with a strong foundation, go with \"Python Crash Course.\" If you're more interested in immediate, practical applications, \"Automate the Boring Stuff with Python\" might be the better fit.",
